/F0 10 Tf
0 0 0 rg
28.346 719.451 Td
(file named bootsect.dat exactly as if it were a hard disk's boot sector. In fact, one could, theoretically, ) Tj
ET
BT
/F0 10 Tf
0 0 0 rg
28.346 705.278 Td
(copy the bootsect.dat file to a drive's boot sector location and cause that operating system to be booted ) Tj
ET
